explanation: UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs: The target function immediately forwards to this function; any unsafe use of <string.h> (on FunctionName or other pointers/fields) will occur here. UT_GetStubEntry: Called by UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs — may return or access stored stub entries that contain string fields or perform string operations (bounds must be inspected). UT_ClearStubEntry: May manipulate or zero string fields in a stub entry (memset/memcpy/etc.); need its implementation to check for out‑of‑bounds accesses. UT_Stub_FindRetvalConfig: May compare or copy strings (strcmp/strncpy/etc.) when locating configuration; its code could violate the rule. UtAssert_Message: Assertion/reporting functions often format or copy strings into internal buffers; must inspect for use of string.h functions that could write beyond buffer bounds. UtAssert_Abort: May call cleanup/reporting routines that manipulate strings — include to ensure no indirect string misuse. UtAssert_GetContext: Returns the assert context (likely including buffers and their sizes); necessary to know buffer sizes and semantics used by UtAssert_Message/Abort. UT_EntryKey_t (type): The type/definition of FuncKey may influence how string operations are performed or which fields/functions are used; include to fully understand parameter usage. Definition of the return type/struct from UT_GetStubEntry (e.g. UT_StubEntry/UT_StubEntry_t): Needed to inspect any string members and how they are accessed/modified. Definition of the context/structure returned by UtAssert_GetContext (e.g. UtAssert_Context_t): Needed to determine buffer sizes and whether string operations in UtAssert_* can exceed those sizes. Any static/global buffers referenced by the above functions: To determine actual object bounds that string functions operate on. Prototypes/definitions of any standard <string.h> functions used by the above functions (e.g. strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strspn): To identify exact string APIs used and to focus the MISRA check on their call sites and argument sizes. Together these symbols let the next analyst inspect where string.h functions are invoked, what buffers/objects they operate on, and whether those accesses can go beyond object bounds.
